Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Test 2. representative tree-level graviton-exchange contribution.\
\>", "Title",
 Editable->False,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981439810443247*^9, 3.98143981492326*^9}, {
  3.985914326252973*^9, 3.9859143266550217`*^9}, {3.986287087928561*^9, 
  3.986287091967786*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c7c8fb3d-9f29-4f40-99c5-\
45218387cbc5"],

Cell["\<\
This example constructs one exchange-channel contribution to four-graviton \
scattering in general relativity. The expression consists of two \
three-graviton vertices connected by one graviton propagator.

The internal momentum flowing through the propagator is p1 + p2. In the first \
vertex the corresponding momentum is written as -(p1 + p2), according to the \
momentum-flow convention used by GravitonVertex.

This is not the full physical four-graviton tree amplitude. A complete \
tree-level four-graviton amplitude would also contain the other exchange \
channels and the four-graviton contact interaction. Moreover, no on-shell \
conditions, transversality conditions, gauge choices, or \
momentum-conservation simplifications are imposed here.

The purpose of this example is to compare the performance and output of \
FeynCalc\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Contract and FeynGravContractor on a physically \
motivated but still fully symbolic tensor expression.

The Timing output reports only the time needed to construct and store the \
input expression; the expression itself is suppressed by the semicolon.\
\>", "Text",
 Editable->False,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.986287109351144*^9, 
  3.98628716897309*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"eae34248-92ca-4e53-81a7-\
f16ff6a163cf"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Clear", "[", "theInput", "]"}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"theInput", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"GravitonVertex", "[", 
      RowBox[{
      "m1", ",", "n1", ",", "p1", ",", "m2", ",", "n2", ",", "p2", ",", "a1", 
       ",", "b1", ",", 
       RowBox[{"-", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"p1", "+", "p2"}], ")"}]}]}], "]"}], 
     RowBox[{"GravitonPropagator", "[", 
      RowBox[{"a1", ",", "b1", ",", "a2", ",", "b2", ",", 
       RowBox[{"p1", "+", "p2"}]}], "]"}], 
     RowBox[{"GravitonVertex", "[", 
      RowBox[{"a2", ",", "b2", ",", 
       RowBox[{"p1", "+", "p2"}], ",", "m3", ",", "n3", ",", "p3", ",", "m4", 
       ",", "n4", ",", "p4"}], "]"}]}]}], ";"}], "//", "Timing"}]}], "Input",
 Editable->False,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981439867294203*^9, 3.981439963418564*^9}, {
   3.9819390190854893`*^9, 3.981939019968445*^9}, 3.981943109572741*^9, {
   3.985863066053251*^9, 3.98586307072232*^9}, {3.985914319068153*^9, 
   3.985914323146422*^9}, {3.985936446246003*^9, 3.985936455601907*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[3]:=",ExpressionUUID->"fabb4321-a92f-4564-8fe8-2a4fe224530e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{"0.028892`", ",", "Null"}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.986294797899057*^9},
 CellLabel->"Out[4]=",ExpressionUUID->"34dc231c-c025-4a1f-9874-158c47ad9be0"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["\<\
The same input expression is now contracted in two different ways.

theOutput0: The expression is contracted using FeynCalc\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
standard Contract routine.
theOutput1: The expression is contracted using FeynGravContractor, which \
sends the tensor-contraction task to Contractor.

Only the timings are printed. The contracted symbolic expressions are stored \
in the variables theOutput0 and theOutput1.\
\>", "Text",
 Editable->False,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.986287350714917*^9, 
  3.986287382053569*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"48929fb0-c314-491d-8a99-\
0278f3c6c6f9"],

