Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Test 4. On-shell four-graviton tree-level amplitude.", "Title",
 Editable->False,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981439810443247*^9, 3.98143981492326*^9}, 
   3.9818863281961203`*^9, {3.981890489247951*^9, 3.981890489370213*^9}, {
   3.981890578468575*^9, 3.981890578602498*^9}, {3.986284016213078*^9, 
   3.9862840163292913`*^9}, {3.986288179033636*^9, 3.98628818279574*^9}, 
   3.9863473891520653`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"735f79ca-3fb3-4743-a2f4-\
f74276879512"],

Cell["\<\
This example computes the complete tree-level four-graviton amplitude in \
general relativity for massless external gravitons. The amplitude is \
assembled from the three exchange diagrams, corresponding to the s-, t- and \
u-channels, together with the four-graviton contact interaction.

The purpose of the test is different from Tests 0--3. Here we no longer \
compare FeynCalc\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Contract with FeynGravContractor at every \
intermediate stage. Instead, we use FeynGravContractor to perform the tensor \
contractions and validate the final on-shell helicity amplitudes against \
known analytic four-graviton results.

All external particles are put on shell only after the tensor building blocks \
have been constructed and contracted with external polarization tensors.\
\>", "Text",
 Editable->False,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.986288193987575*^9, 
  3.986288232194916*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"41485933-7657-4050-b94b-\
55c40a7093d9"],

Cell["\<\
Generic exchange-channel building block.

The function \[ScriptCapitalM]s defines a reusable tensor expression for one \
graviton-exchange diagram: two three-graviton vertices connected by one \
graviton propagator. At this stage the expression is still an off-shell \
tensor object with free external Lorentz indices. It has not yet been \
contracted with external polarization tensors and should not be interpreted \
as a physical on-shell amplitude by itself.

The internal momentum is p1 + p2. The factor FeynAmpDenominatorExplicit is \
used to rewrite the propagator denominator explicitly in terms of scalar \
products, which makes the subsequent Mandelstam-variable simplifications more \
direct.

This definition is evaluated once and then reused with permuted external legs \
to obtain the s-, t- and u-channel contributions.\
\>", "Text",
 Editable->False,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.986288254413529*^9, 
  3.986288299995151*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"27050ff4-5aa2-4021-914e-\
7da6ca95ca9c"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
